ce:section.ce:para:
We further examined the therapeutic efficacy of Lys-CNGs-260 (50 µg mL−1) with different dosing frequencies (at 12, 48, and 96 h intervals) and compared it with commercial eye drops, CsA [(0.005% w/w (ca. 50 µg mL−1) or 0.05% w/w (ca. 500 µg mL−1); once at 12 h]. The Lys-CNGs-260, even with only one dose (one dose per 96 h) could effectively mitigate the corneal epithelial injury caused by chronic instillation of benzalkonium chloride in rabbits during the entire follow-up period of 4 days (Fig. 4
                        ), indicating that Lys-CNGs-260 possess the potential to prolong the residence time on the ocular surface. All groups showed a maximum fluorescein staining score of 9 after benzalkonium chloride administration, which represents high severity of disease in the DES animal model (Fig. 4
                        A, lower panel). The Ctrl and CsA (0.005% w/w, same concentration as Lys-CNGs-260) groups scored higher than Lys-CNGs-260 during the follow-up period, suggesting that repeated administration of PBS and low concentrations of CsA is ineffective for the treatment of severe DES. The fluorescein score of CsA (0.05% w/w; one dose per 12 h, a total of 8 doses) groups on day 4 post-treatment was 2.7 ± 0.6, which was not significantly different (p>0.05) from the Lys-CNGs-260 groups treated with only one dose. It is also interesting to note that the Lys-CNGs-260 treatment group administered every 12 h or 48 h showed none-to-mild staining on day 4 post-treatment, with a staining score of 1. The Lys-CNGs-260 showed a better treatment effect than the CsA groups, even under the conditions of 10-fold lower concentration (50 µg mL−1 versus 0.05% CsA) and less frequent dosing. The therapeutic effects of CsA (0.05%) with one dose per 48 or 96 h are similar to that of PBS Ctrl groups, indicating that frequent doses of commercial CsA eye drops are inevitable.
